{
  "texts": [
    "The approximate posterior is defined as:q (z 0:T | x 0:T, a 1:T) = T t=0 q (z t | z <t, a ≤t, x t)(2)The conditioning on previous states z <t and actions a ≤t appears multiple times.",
    "RSSM uses a shared GRU to compress z <t and a ≤t into a deterministic encoding h t:h t = GRU (h t-1, MLP (concat [z t-1, a t]))(3)This is then used to compute the sufficient statistics of the prior, likelihood, and posterior: The training objective is to maximize the evidence lower bound (ELBO):p (z t | z <t, a ≤t) = MLP (h t), p (x t | z ≤t, a ≤t) = N (x t, 1), xt = Decoder (concat [h t, z t]), q (z t | z <t, a ≤t, x t) = MLP (concat [h t, e t]), e t = Encoder (x t).",
    "(4)log p (x 0:T | a 1:T) ≥ E q T t=0 log p (x t | z ≤t, a ≤t) -L KL (q (z t | z <t, a ≤t, x t), p (z t | z <t, a ≤t))(5)2) Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture (JEPA) [1] marks a paradigm shift in predictive modeling by focusing on representation space rather than direct, detailed predictions.",
    "As shown in Fig. 4, by abstracting input (x) and target (y) through dual encoders into representations (s x and s y), and leveraging a latent variable (z) for prediction, JEPA achieves a significant leap in efficiency and accuracy.",
    "This model excels in filtering out noise and irrelevancies, concentrating on the essence of the predictive task."
  ]
}